atch the medium; how viewers accept, miss, ignore, negotiate, and resist media messages; and how television’s influence works within the local cultural context to modify social identities, consumption patterns, and worldviews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aEthnologyzBrazilzGurupa (Para). 0aSocial changezBrazilzBrazilzGurupa (Para). 0aTelevision and culturezBrazilzGurupa (Para). 0aTelevision and familieszBrazilzGurupa (Para). 0aTelevision in popular culturexHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aHinote, Brian P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292745186423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292745186/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK